summary:
The Security Council, recalling its previous resolutions on terrorism, expresses gravest concern about ISIL and Al-Qaida's presence, ideology, and actions. It emphasizes sanctions' importance in maintaining international peace and security, particularly in countering terrorism. The Council stresses the 1267/1989/2253 ISIL (Da'esh) and Al-Qaida Sanctions Committee's role in identifying non-compliance and determining the course of action. 

The Council reaffirms the need to combat terrorism by all means, in accordance with the Charter and international law, and recognizes the importance of development, security, and human rights in counter-terrorism strategies. It also recognizes the need to increase fairness and effectiveness in the Committee's rules and procedures, reiterating the Office of the Ombudsperson's importance.

The Council:
1. Encourages Member States to submit listing requests and additional information to keep the ISIL (Da'esh) & Al-Qaida Sanctions List up-to-date and utilize exemptions to the measures;
2. Requests the Analytical Support and Sanctions Monitoring Team to study exemptions procedures and provide recommendations within 9 months;
3. Decides to remain actively seized of the matter.
